<subSubSection id="34AD6563067EF1593312E8AEB3BBEE8D" pageId="5" pageNumber="134" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="7C0836E8067EF1593312E8AEB3BBEE8D" blockId="5.[113,752,669,757]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">
<emphasis id="4EC3EAFA067EF1593312E8AEB2B8EECD" bold="true" box="[113,243,669,693]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is a Latin adjective referring to the presence of an embolic-like process [= radical apophysis] in the embolic division.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="34AD6563067EF1593312E92EB0F4EF0D" pageId="5" pageNumber="134" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="7C0836E8067EF1593312E92EB0F4EF0D" blockId="5.[113,752,797,885]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">
<emphasis id="4EC3EAFA067EF1593312E92EB2ADEF4D" bold="true" box="[113,230,797,821]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The new species is diagnosed by the presence of an embolus-like radical apophysis in the embolic division and by the characteristic shape of the epigynal cavity.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="34AD6563067EF1593312E9AEB097EB6D" pageId="5" pageNumber="134" type="description">
<paragraph id="7C0836E8067EF1593312E9AEB0BBE9ED" blockId="5.[112,754,925,1429]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">
<emphasis id="4EC3EAFA067EF1593312E9AEB2B5EFCD" bold="true" box="[113,254,925,949]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">Description.</emphasis>
Male 
<typeStatus id="A30C884A067EF1593229E9AEB3E7EFCD" box="[330,428,925,949]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">holotype</typeStatus>
. Total length 2.03. Carapace 0.90 long, 0.75 wide, unmodified, as shown in 
<figureCitation id="E48C2A6D067EF159313DE98EB0D6EFAD" box="[606,669,957,981]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[135,179,1902,1924]" captionTargetBox="[138,1473,351,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-8@2.[120,1488,349,1897]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 1–6. Habitus of Vietnagone silvatica, new species (1–3) and Nasoonaria pseudoembolica, new species (4–6). 1, 4, male holotype; 2, 3, 5, 6, female paratype; 1, 2, 4, 5, dorsal view; 3, 6, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577001" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577001/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
, yellow to pale brown. Chelicerae 0.35 long, a mastidion absent. Legs yellow. Leg I 3.51 long (0.93+0.28+0.95+0.75+0.60); IV 3.41 long (0.90+0.28+0.88+0.85+0.50). Chaetotaxy: 2.2.1.1. Length of spines 1.5–2.5 diameters of leg segment. All metatarsi with a trichobothrium. TmI 0.64. Palp (
<figureCitation id="E48C2A6D067EF15931D8EE6EB2F0E8ED" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[135,179,1926,1948]" captionTargetBox="[138,1474,297,1911]" captionTargetId="figure-8@4.[132,1474,283,1921]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 14–20. Details of palpal and epigynal structure of Nasoonaria pseudoembolica, new species. 14–17, male holotype; 18–20, female paratype. 14, 15, right palp, retrolateral and prolateral views, respectively; 16, palpal tibia, dorsal view; 17, embolic division; 18, 19, epigyne, ventral views, different aspects; 20, epigyne, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577005" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577005/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">Figs. 14–17</figureCitation>
): tibia wide, elongated, with a retrolateral obtuse outgrowth. Prolateral edge of tibia undulate. Paracymbium L-shaped, with a long and narrow distal part, uncinate apically. Distal suprategular apophysis hypertrophied, falcate. Median membrane relatively narrow and long, tongue-shaped. Embolic division with a small and partly membraneous radix. Embolus thin, long, whip-shaped; a dark, falcate, embolus-like, radical apophysis starting at base of embolus. Abdomen 1.13 long, 0.65 wide, dorsal pattern as in 
<figureCitation id="E48C2A6D067EF15931C9EF4EB0A7E9ED" box="[682,748,1405,1429]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[135,179,1902,1924]" captionTargetBox="[138,1473,351,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-8@2.[120,1488,349,1897]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 1–6. Habitus of Vietnagone silvatica, new species (1–3) and Nasoonaria pseudoembolica, new species (4–6). 1, 4, male holotype; 2, 3, 5, 6, female paratype; 1, 2, 4, 5, dorsal view; 3, 6, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577001" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577001/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7C0836E8067EF1593312EF8EB097EB6D" blockId="5.[110,754,1469,1813]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">
Female. Total length 2.00. Carapace 0.75 long, 0.68 wide, unmodified, as shown in 
<figureCitation id="E48C2A6D067EF15932F0EFEEB392E98D" box="[403,473,1501,1525]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[135,179,1902,1924]" captionTargetBox="[138,1473,351,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-8@2.[120,1488,349,1897]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 1–6. Habitus of Vietnagone silvatica, new species (1–3) and Nasoonaria pseudoembolica, new species (4–6). 1, 4, male holotype; 2, 3, 5, 6, female paratype; 1, 2, 4, 5, dorsal view; 3, 6, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577001" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577001/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
. Chelicerae 0.33 long, a mastidion absent.Leg I 2.93 long (0.80+0.25+0.75+0.63+0.50); IV 3.11 long (0.88+0.23+0.75+0.75+0.50). All metatarsi with a trichobothrium. TmI 0.64. Abdomen 1.25 long, 0.83 wide, dorsal pattern as in 
<figureCitation id="E48C2A6D067EF15932EFEC6EB384EA0D" box="[396,463,1629,1653]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[135,179,1902,1924]" captionTargetBox="[138,1473,351,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-8@2.[120,1488,349,1897]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 1–6. Habitus of Vietnagone silvatica, new species (1–3) and Nasoonaria pseudoembolica, new species (4–6). 1, 4, male holotype; 2, 3, 5, 6, female paratype; 1, 2, 4, 5, dorsal view; 3, 6, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577001" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577001/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
. Epigyne (
<figureCitation id="E48C2A6D067EF1593127EC6EB0DAEA0D" box="[580,657,1629,1653]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[135,179,1902,1924]" captionTargetBox="[138,1473,351,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-8@2.[120,1488,349,1897]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 1–6. Habitus of Vietnagone silvatica, new species (1–3) and Nasoonaria pseudoembolica, new species (4–6). 1, 4, male holotype; 2, 3, 5, 6, female paratype; 1, 2, 4, 5, dorsal view; 3, 6, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577001" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577001/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">Figs. 6</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="E48C2A6D067EF15931FDEC6EB0ADEA0D" box="[670,742,1629,1653]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[135,179,1926,1948]" captionTargetBox="[138,1474,297,1911]" captionTargetId="figure-8@4.[132,1474,283,1921]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 14–20. Details of palpal and epigynal structure of Nasoonaria pseudoembolica, new species. 14–17, male holotype; 18–20, female paratype. 14, 15, right palp, retrolateral and prolateral views, respectively; 16, palpal tibia, dorsal view; 17, embolic division; 18, 19, epigyne, ventral views, different aspects; 20, epigyne, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577005" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577005/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">18–20</figureCitation>
): epigynal cavity shallow, trapeziform, its lateral walls slightly concave, anterior part of cavity with a prominence. Posterior median plate [= dorsal plate] short and wide, with a hollow at posterior edge. Receptacles bean-shaped. Body (
<figureCitation id="E48C2A6D067EF15931FCECEEB2CAEB6D" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[135,179,1902,1924]" captionTargetBox="[138,1473,351,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-8@2.[120,1488,349,1897]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 1–6. Habitus of Vietnagone silvatica, new species (1–3) and Nasoonaria pseudoembolica, new species (4–6). 1, 4, male holotype; 2, 3, 5, 6, female paratype; 1, 2, 4, 5, dorsal view; 3, 6, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577001" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577001/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">Figs. 5, 6</figureCitation>
) and leg colouration, as well as chaetotaxy as in male.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="34AD6563067EF1593312ED0EB062EB8D" pageId="5" pageNumber="134" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="7C0836E8067EF1593312ED0EB062EB8D" blockId="5.[113,753,1853,2037]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">
<emphasis id="4EC3EAFA067EF1593312ED0EB314EB2D" bold="true" box="[113,351,1853,1877]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">Taxonomic remarks.</emphasis>
The species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="BBB74D6B067EF1593110ED0DB3ADEB0D" authority="Wunderlich &amp; Song, 1995" authorityName="Wunderlich &amp; Song" authorityYear="1995" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Nasoonaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="134" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinensis">
<emphasis id="4EC3EAFA067EF1593110ED0DB28EEB0D" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">Nasoonaria sinensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="18264B19067EF15933AFED6EB3ADEB0D" author="Wunderlich J &amp; Song DX" box="[204,486,1885,1909]" firstAuthor="Wunderlich" journalOrPublisher="Beitrage zur Araneologie" pageId="5" pageNumber="134" pagination="343 - 351" part="4" refId="ref3241" refString="Wunderlich J &amp; Song DX (1995) Four new spider species of the families Anapidae, Linyphiidae and Nesticidae from a tropical rain forest area of SW-China. Beitrage zur Araneologie, 4: 343 - 351." title="Four new spider species of the families Anapidae, Linyphiidae and Nesticidae from a tropical rain forest area of SW-China" type="journal article" year="1995">Wunderlich &amp; Song, 1995</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished by the simple male palpal tibia (vs. strongly modified in 
<taxonomicName id="BBB74D6B067EF15931BBED4DB28CEBCD" authorityName="Wunderlich &amp; Song" authorityYear="1995" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Nasoonaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="134" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinensis">
<emphasis id="4EC3EAFA067EF15931BBED4DB28CEBCD" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">N. sinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the presence of an embolus-like process in the embolic division, and by the presence of an epigynal cavity in the female (vs. absent in 
<taxonomicName id="BBB74D6B067EF15932C6EDEDB053EB8D" authorityName="Wunderlich &amp; Song" authorityYear="1995" box="[421,536,2014,2037]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Nasoonaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="134" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinensis">
<emphasis id="4EC3EAFA067EF15932C6EDEDB053EB8D" box="[421,536,2014,2037]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">N. sinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="34AD6563067EF1593312E22EB372E42D" pageId="5" pageNumber="134" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="7C0836E8067EF1593312E22EB372E42D" blockId="5.[113,752,2077,2131]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">
<emphasis id="4EC3EAFA067EF1593312E22EB34FE44D" bold="true" box="[113,260,2077,2101]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">Distribution.</emphasis>
So far known only from the 
<typeStatus id="A30C884A067EF1593128E22EB032E44D" box="[587,633,2077,2101]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">type</typeStatus>
locality in southern 
<collectingCountry id="04A07678067EF15933B5E20EB37EE42D" box="[214,309,2109,2133]" name="Vietnam" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
